<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Atriplex prostrata </i>is a salt-tolerant non-native from Eurasia that is widespread in the northern hemisphere. This low-growing annual establishes on drying mud that is seasonally flooded with brackish water. It has been planted in managed wetlands for its nutritious seed, which is a food source for wintering waterfowl. Seeds are polymorphic with different germination responses correlated to salinity, temperature, and light (Carter and Ungar 2003, Khan and Ungar 1984). Plants become fully grown by late summer. The <i>Jepson Manual </i>(Hickman 1993) formerly used the synonym <i>A. triangularis</i>, though now recognizes <i>A. prostrata</i> (Jepson Flora Project 2021).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Cotula coronopifolia </i>is a non-native from South Africa, with bright yellow, discoid flower heads. Plants are annuals or short-lived perennials that spread by stolons. It is very salt tolerant, with reddish stems and green, blade-shaped leaves that are coated with a shiny cuticle to retain moisture. This species prefers muddy, anoxic wetlands and brackish water. It can also be found in the wetter patches of vernal pools at moderately high salinities. <br/>
<br/>
Both species are indicative of disturbed conditions in alkaline or saline wetlands. Both are early seral plants; they may be abundant to sparse from year to year depending on disturbance regime and salinity. Thus, we place them into this one vegetation type which constitutes an ephemeral, seasonally flooded marsh type at intermediate tidal elevations with relatively high salinities (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000, Pickart 2006). Stands occur usually in relatively narrow bands along the upper margins of brackish or salt marshes and sloughs, and sometimes as extensive monocultures (Pickart 2006, Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Sikes et al. 2021). Ecologically, the most closely related native types may be the <i>Distichlis spicata </i>and <i>Frankenia salina </i>alliances. As a result of flooding, stands of the <i>Typha (angustifolia, domingensis, latifolia)</i> alliance and other freshwater plants may occur adjacent to or replace them. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
