    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). Stands at San Francisco Bay estuary are usually on the middle to upper edge of the marsh (Baye et al. 2000), adjacent to stands of the <i>Distichlis spicata, Frankenia salina, Juncus arcticus (var. balticus, mexicanus), </i>and <i>Leymus triticoides </i>alliances.
Sampled stand on the San Mateo coast, 1.5 miles south of Pescadero (Sikes et al. 2021).  Expected stands in other areas based on CCH and Cal-IPC records (CCH 2017, Cal-IPC 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ac-d). Expected stands based on CCH records (CCH 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ac-t, Ay). Sampled stands throughout Suisun Marsh have <i>Argentina egedii, Distichlis spicata, Eleocharis macrostachya, Frankenia salina, Bolboschoenus maritimus, Sesuvium verrucosum, Spergularia marina, </i>and other natives (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000).  Expected stands in other areas of section based on CCH and Cal-IPC data (CCH 2017, Cal-IPC 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa). Expected stands based on CCH records (CCH 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Da-f, Dh-i, Dl). Expected stands based on CCH records (CCH 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-e, Ag-l). Stands exist in Humboldt Bay National Wildlife Refuge; they usually occur in highly saline, acidic soils on newly scraped areas and flooded or exposed bare mud late into the summer season (Pickart 2006). Sampled stand near Novato Creek of <i>Cotula coronopifolia is in a low-lying slough</i> (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021).  <i>Atriplex prostrata </i>is a dominant in non-tidal seasonal wetlands of the Loch Lomond Marin in Marin Co. (Josselyn and DeGraff 2003).  Expected stands in other areas based on CCH and Cal-IPC data (CCH 2017, Cal-IPC 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Expected stands in section based on CCH records and Cal-IPC data (CCH 2017, Cal-IPC 2018).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bf, Bj-k). Expected stands based on CCH records (CCH 2017).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Atriplex prostrata </i>and <i>Cotula coronopifolia </i>are sources of winter feed for ducks and other waterfowl (Burns 2003). Disturbances within diked wetlands are stimulatory for this type, and both species are major components of managed brackish and saline marshes (Baye 2000).  Land managers establish stands by seeding, disking, scraping, or clearing areas. The stands fluctuate annually and may not persist with changes in flooding regimes or colonization by <i>Distichlis spicata, Frankenia salina, Juncus arcticus, Sarcocornia pacifica, Schoenoplectus </i>spp., and other perennials. </div>
</div>

    

    

